          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Some of us are old =
enough to remember when the publicity firm PMK kinda ruled the Hollywood ta=
lent landscape. As recently as the early 2000s, the trio of <b>Pat Kingsley=
</b>, <b>Leslee Dart</b>, and (until her 2003 retirement) <b>Lois Smith</b>=
 was considered the iron claw of celebrity P.R., especially after PMK merge=
d with Huvane Baum Halls and <i>before</i> Dart was fired in 2004. Of cours=
e, it was far from a monopoly=E2=80=94Rogers &amp; Cowan, also owned by the=
 marketing and advertising behemoth Interpublic Group, was powerful, too=E2=
=80=94even if that pre-internet era now seems as quaint as a <i>Premiere</i=
> cover. Back then, as a young lawyer, and then journalist, I knew not to s=
crew around with Kingsley or one of her PMK minions.      <br/> <br/>So muc=
h so that in 2005, after <b>Tom Cruise</b> nuked his public persona on <b>O=
prah</b>=E2=80=99s couch and in the
=E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re glib=E2=80=9D <b>Matt Lauer</b> interview, the melt=
down was attributed within the industry as much to Cruise=E2=80=99s split f=
rom Kingsley as his descent into Scientology lunacy. A few years later, Cru=
ise=E2=80=99s profile was back under careful supervision=E2=80=94but by <b>=
Amanda Lundberg</b> at 42 West, Dart=E2=80=99s new startup, not by PMK. It =
