 All because Berger believes the 2PM Sharp defectors left the =E2=80=9Cwron=
g=E2=80=9D way=E2=80=94and likely thinks she can extract some go-away money=
=2E  <br/><br/>If that sounds famili=
ar, it=E2=80=99s how CAA described its re=
cent lawsuit against the agents who bailed to start Range Media Partners. E=
ntrenched players, especially those in challenged businesses, talk a lot ab=
out the =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwrong=E2=80=9D way to leave co=
mpanies. But the =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D way usually corresponds to ensurin=
g
that the entrenched player isn=E2=80=99t made to feel remotely uncomfortabl=
e. That=E2=80=99s why CAA <i>blesses</i> those who leave for its preferred =
jobs, and why managing partner <b>Richard Lovett</b> instead spearheaded th=
e =E2=80=9Clawless midnight raid=E2=80=9D litigation against a group of age=
nts who defected to rival UTA in 2015. Same with the Range guys, whose exit=
 was considered so disruptive and disrespectful by CAA C.E.O. <b>Bryan Lour=
d</b> that the agency turned a private arbitration over financial obligatio=
ns into a public lawsuit for =E2=80=9Cunfair competition.=E2=80=9D Again, r=
egardless of whether it=E2=80=99s legally warranted or not, it=E2=80=99s a =
weenie move.    <br/></td>
