          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">At the big firms, i=
ndividual publicists are often commissioned a percentage of the fees from b=
usiness they sign or, sometimes, from the clients they primarily service. O=
ther firms won=E2=80=99t share fees at all, instead paying set salaries. I =
mention all this because it explains why the talent publicity business has =
become a diaspora of smaller shops. Flacking is a fee-for-service business,=
 so unlike with commission-based reps, there=E2=80=99s little incentive to =
stick around a company like PMK if you have your own clients and your own r=
elationships. Most stars don=E2=80=99t even know the parent company of thei=
r publicist=E2=80=99s firm. Plus, it=E2=80=99s not like the publicist benef=
its from a long tail of revenue from a movie or show=E2=80=94revenue that i=
s forfeited if, say, an agent bails on CAA.<br/><br/>For that reason, among=
 others, the list of top talent P.R. firms born from
PMK is long and distinguished: Slate (<b>Simon Halls</b>, <b>Robin Baum</b>=
, and <b>Stephen Huvane</b>), Viewpoint (<b>Jennifer Allen</b>, <b>Melissa =
Kates</b>, and others), Kovert (<b>Lewis Kay</b>), Align (<b>Nicole Perez-K=
rueger</b>), Full Coverage (<b>Kristen Foster</b>), Luna (<b>Lauren Ausland=
er</b>), <b>Jill Fritzo</b>, <b>Ame Van Iden</b>, <b>Cheryl Maisel</b>=E2=
=80=94the list goes on. And now, 2PM Sharp. That=E2=80=99s not even includi=
ng <b>Michael Nyman</b>=E2=80=99s 2018 exit as C.E.O. of PMK to start an in=
vestment and advisory firm.<br/><br/>You don=E2=80=99t need me to tell you =
that talent P.R. is a much different job today than it was even 10 years ag=
o. Now, a well-timed Deuxmoi post can be far more effective than an <i>EW</=
i> cover. <i>Chicken Shop Date</i> is the new <i>Tonight Show</i>. Digital =
creators and the influencer economy are the growth areas. And most of the f=
irms offer what is essentially digital brand management as well as traditio=
nal P.R. There=E2=80=99s a generational shift
at these firms, too. Publicists, like other reps, grow with their clients. =
And while I=E2=80=99m generalizing: If you look at the PMK client list, the=
re=E2=80=99s a ton of older stars like <b>Kevin Costner</b>, or <b>Billy Cr=
ystal</b>, or <b>Eddie Murphy</b>. Berger, in a recent presentation to Shea=
 and others, is said to have laid out a strategy to grow the more youthful =
categories.  <br/><br/>Don=E2=80=99t get me wrong: PMK still does fine. Tho=
se legacy stars, like <b>Denzel Washington</b> and <b>Billy Bob Thornton</b=
>=E2=80=94or even those one generation down like <b>Chris Pratt</b>=E2=80=
=94still pay the bills, and the unit is said to be profitable. Hollywood ta=
lent P.R. represents a sexy yet small part of these large firms=E2=80=99 ov=
erall branding and corporate marketing business. (I=E2=80=99m also pretty s=
ure that <b>Diddy</b>, a big PMK client for a while, is no longer on the ro=
ster.) While parent IPG doesn=E2=80=99t break out financials for PMK, the O=
ctagon unit where PMK resides is doing well=E2=80=94much better than
IPG overall, whose share price is down 11 percent this year. And PMK isn=E2=
=80=99t alone in suffering major defections; rivals ID PR and 42 West have =
also lost groups who started their own firms.   <br/><br/>But PMK is not wh=
at it was, and suing over a group of defectors raises a red flag. Regardles=
s of whether they exited the =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwrong=E2=
=80=9D way, the message to the broader community is that this loss really h=
urt PMK, and the leadership doesn=E2=80=99t have a different way to respond=
=2E It=E2=80=99s tough to spin that.  <br/></td>
